---
title: "How to Decide Between Custom Development and Off-the-Shelf Software for Your Business"
date: "2023-04-18"
summary: "Decide between custom development and off-the-shelf software with a framework that accounts for total cost, not just the price tag."
coverImage: ""
tags:
  - "Development"
author: "Redevise"
---

You need software. You can buy something off the shelf for $200 a month. You can build something custom for $80,000. The math seems obvious. It is not.

Off-the-shelf software is built for a general audience. It handles 70 percent of what you need. The other 30 percent requires workarounds. The workarounds are free in dollar terms. They are expensive in time.

[Custom software](/services#software) is built for you. It handles 95 percent of what you need. The other 5 percent is built during the project. There are no workarounds. There is a build.

Here is the framework.

Calculate the off-the-shelf total cost. Subscription: $200 a month. Workaround time: 5 hours a week at $50 per hour. Integration: $2,000 one-time. Over three years: subscription is $7,200, workarounds are $39,000, integration is $2,000. Total: $48,200.

Calculate the custom total cost. Build: $80,000. Maintenance: $12,000 a year. Over three years: build is $80,000, maintenance is $36,000. Total: $116,000.

The off-the-shelf option is cheaper. But the $39,000 in workaround time is not visible on the invoice. It is paid in staff time. In frustration. In errors caused by the workarounds.

I advised a client in 2024. The off-the-shelf option was cheaper over three years. But the workarounds were causing errors that cost $20,000 a year in rework. The custom option was cheaper over five years.

The decision depends on the time horizon. Under three years, off-the-shelf often wins. Over five years, custom often wins. The workaround cost is the variable.

Calculate both totals. Include the workarounds. The honest number is different from the sticker price.
